\textbf{Word Problem:}

A factory produces wooden rods that are each $\dfrac{3}{4}$ metre long. These rods are bundled together in groups of $5$ for delivery. \begin{enumerate}
  \item How long is one bundle of $5$ rods altogether? 
  \item If an order requires the factory to divide $\dfrac{3}{4}$ metre equally among $3$ machines, how much rod length does each machine receive? 
  \item After producing $2$ bundles and using up $\dfrac{3}{4}$ metre of rod (shared among the machines as above), what is the total rod length the factory still has from $20$ rods, if it started with $20$ rods? 
\end{enumerate}

response_dict.solution:
\textbf{Solution:}

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \text{One bundle has 5 rods, each } \dfrac{3}{4} \text{ metre.}

\[ 5 \times \dfrac{3}{4} = \dfrac{15}{4} = 3 \dfrac{3}{4} \text{ metres} \]

  \item \text{Dividing } \dfrac{3}{4} \text{ metre equally among 3 machines:}

\[ \dfrac{3}{4} \div 3 = \dfrac{3}{4} \times \dfrac{1}{3} = \dfrac{3}{12} = \dfrac{1}{4} \text{ metre each} \]

  \item \text{Total rod length from 20 rods:}

\[ \text{Each rod is } \dfrac{3}{4} \text{ metre} \Rightarrow 20 \times \dfrac{3}{4} = \dfrac{60}{4} = 15 \text{ metres} \]

\text{After producing 2 bundles, number of rods used:}
\[ 2 \times 5 = 10 \text{ rods used} \]
\text{Rod length used: } 10 \times \dfrac{3}{4} = \dfrac{30}{4} = 7 \dfrac{2}{4} = 7 \dfrac{1}{2} \text{ metres} \]

\text{Rod used for machines: } \dfrac{3}{4} \text{ metre}

\text{Total rod length used: } 7 \dfrac{1}{2} + \dfrac{3}{4} = 7 \dfrac{2}{4} + \dfrac{3}{4} = 7 \dfrac{5}{4} = 8 \dfrac{1}{4} \text{ metres} 

\text{Total rod length left: }
\[ 15 - 8 \dfrac{1}{4} = 15 - 8.25 = 6.75 \text{ metres} = 6 \dfrac{3}{4} \text{ metres} \]
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Final Answers:}
1. $3 \dfrac{3}{4}$ metres per bundle\newline
2. $\dfrac{1}{4}$ metre per machine\newline
3. $6 \dfrac{3}{4}$ metres of rod left after all the usage.

